One year ago, on the 1st of April 2018 a group of people living in a refugee camp in northern Greece, Katsikas, and some team members from the organization Soup and Socks embarked on an adventure of running a half-marathon to raise awareness about the situation of refugees in Greece and for people’s FREEDOM OF MOVEMENT. One year later the situation for the people living in Camp Katsikas remains unchanged. Now, the camp accommodates 993 people from different parts of the world who are in a stagnant situation. Together with some of the runners who participated last year and some new runners we want to participate in the full MARATHON in Olympia to let people know we are still running – that the situation of refugees in Greece is unchanged and that the basic human right of freedom of movement is still being violated.This year, we want to raise €3.500 to enable people from Camp Katsikas and Habibi.Works to run a full marathon on the 31st of March 2019. The money raised will cover the entire costs for participating in the run; registration fees, running gear such as shoes, shirts and shorts, transportation from and to the race, accommodation, and food.Every cent that will be raised on top of the costs for the run, will go directly into realizing people’s projects in our maker space Habibi.Works. Powered by the German NGO Soup and Socks e.V., Habibi.Works is an intercultural maker space, which provides platforms for education, empowerment and encounter. In eleven different working areas, people from nearby refugee camps and locals have the possibility to get active, create, take first steps of integration and share knowledge. In case we do not manage to fundraise the target amount, the costs will be covered for as many people as can join with the fundraised money. Help us make sure all the 15 highly motivated and enthusiastic runners can participate!We will be running the Olympia Marathon in the historic ancient city of Olympia. For all the supporters who want to encourage the runners during the race, we will cheer together at the finish line in Ancient Olypmia.Support the runners in their quest to run for their right to movement at the Olympia Marathon.The ImpactEnabling people whose lives have been put on hold to participate in sports activities will benefit the participants in a number of ways:
General mental and physical health benefit of sports;
Community building through training, preparation and participating together despite nationality, gender, ethnicity and age;
Working towards a goal and an achievement in a context where lives have been put on hold and people are continuously waiting;
Giving people a stage to raise awareness about the ongoing challenges asylum seekers face in Greece;
Amplify the supporting network of Habibi.Works to ensure the sustainable development of the services we are offering to empower people.
Meet the Runners:AliAli Ahmad is from Afghanistan and he is 25 years old. Ali has been in Greece for one year and five months, of which he lived one year and two months on Lesvos, and three months in Katsikas. Before Ali came to Greece he was in the army in Afghanistan. When it got too dangerous for him to stay he left to Greece.“I have been running my whole live, in Afghanistan, in Lesvos and now here in Katsikas. It is very important for me to run, for both body and mind. Without running I would only sit in my container, which would create problems for my mind”. MamadouMamadou is from Guinea. He is 19 years old. He came to Greece in January 2018 and was moved to Katsikas in October 2018. He worked in a supermarket, a family business, before leaving from Guinea.“I love to run because it is my dream to become a professional football player. In Guinea there are no events like this and I want to participate in the marathon to make my country proud and be proud of my nationality. If I do sport it diminishes my stress and enforces my physical strength”.AbdoullahAbdoullah is 21 years old and is from Guinea. In Guinea Abdoullah played football professionally for fc loubah (before in the 1st division and now in the second division). On the 26th of December, just over year ago, Abdoullah came to Greece. He spent 9 months in Lesvos camp before coming to Katsikas Camp."Sport is good. When I have some problems and I go and do sport it makes me feel good. It is a good training and I feel good running. In all my life I do sport and when I do this I feel good. When I do sport I forget the situation on the island and the situation in the camp.I want to continue my football in Europe this is my job and my passion."AhmadAhmed is from Syria. He is 22 years old. He has been in Greece for 1.5 years, of which he spent six months in Samos and more than one year in Katsikas. In Syria he worked in his own supermarket. Ahmed also ran the first half marathon we did one year ago.“I love all sports. It is important for my body, and a healthy body is important for a good life. This year I want to participate in the marathon because after every race I run, I am encouraged to go one step further. We ran half a marathon last year, and 30 kilometers in September. Now I want to run a full marathon. I still want to be the first one. I am encouraged to train every day because we run together. By joining in the marathon I feel more integrated in Europe, because there are people from all over Europe. This is very important for me”. MohammadMohammad is 20 years old and comes from Baghdad in Iraq. In Baghdad he played football and his dream is to become a professional football player. Two years ago he left Iraq and came to Greece. He was on Lesvos in Mouria camp for one year and a half living in a tent before coming to Katsikas in October 2018.“I want to be fit for football. My dream is to become a professional football player with Liverpool. For me sport is very important. Here the people only eat and sleep. It is so boring. For me playing sport is a way to tire my mind and body”. JaganaMohammad aka Jagana is 21 years old and comes from Senegal. Jagana grew up with sports playing an important part in his life. Him and his family cultivated a piece of land. He came to Greece on the 6th of November 2017. He spent nine months on Lesvos, a lot of the time he was in Mouria. In September 2018 he was moved to Katsikas and has been actively playing football ever since.“Sport is important for my health and I like all kinds of sports. If I don’t do sports I will not feel good. I met a bunch of guys during a Gambia versus Guinea game in Lesvos. After coming to Katikas the people that I met in Lesvos and I started training together. Running is very important for a football player to stay fit and in shape”.HenryHenry is from Nigeria. In May he will turn 22 years old. In Nigeria Henry was playing football professionally. In 2016 he left Nigeria and went to Istanbul, Turkey. There he also found a team to play football. After a year in Turkey, Henry came to Greece in 2017 and has been living in Mouria camp for eleven months before coming to Katsikas. Now he plays football here with some of the people he met in Mouria.“Sport gives me joy and happiness. I want to use sport to achieve my goals, sport is my dream. I love to play football. It gives me joy to play in a team. I want to run the marathon because I want to be fit and challenge my body”. GhazemGhazem is from Afghanistan, Mazarshrif. He is 32 years old. Before coming to Greece, he worked as a welder. He left Afghanistan in 2004 to Iran. In August 2017 he left Iran and has been in Greece since then. In April last year he ran the half-marathon in Olympia and also participated in the 30km Lake Run in Ioannina."I run for my health. I just want to be healthy. Also, we need to spread the word that people are still living in camps, their lives put on hold and they are just waiting until decisions are made for them"BaraaBaraa is from Burkina Faso, Ouagadougou. He has been in Greece for one year and three months, of which 1 year on Lesvos, and 3 months in Katsikas. In Burkina Faso he worked as a tailor, he liked his job a lot and is still sewing a lot in Habibi.Works.“I played a lot of sports in Burkina Faso. I played football and I ran a lot. Now I want to put my skills in use again and join in the marathon. Running is important for me because it makes me feel good, both physically and mentally”. ElskeElske is from the Netherlands, the Hague. She is 27 years old. She has been working in Habibi.Works since she came to Greece on a bicycle in June 2017. She has been organizing and setting up a running group with people living in the camp. Successfully they have participated in the half-marathon, a 10km race in Ioannina and the 30km Lake Run in Ioannina."I want to run because it is a great way to relax my mind and interact with our amazing neighbors from camp Katsikas. It is a great way to bond with people and strive for a common goal. Furthermore, I think it is very important that the situation of refugees here in Greece is addressed. People in Europe seem to have forgotten about them, but at the same time they are still here, stuck in Greece without any freedom of movement."KikiKiki is from Germany, Berlin. She is 27 years old. She is working in Habibi.Works and has been in Greece since February 2017. Together with Elske, she has set up a running group that runs together most mornings. Until now they have participated in three races with the biggest one, the marathon, yet to come."I want to run to raise awareness for peoples' situation in Greece and stand in solidarity with people who are stuck here against their will. Moreover, running helps me to stay fit, is an outlet to keep me balanced and is a great team building experience"   AhmadAhmad is Kurdish and is from Syria from Afrin. He went to school in Aleppo and was able to finish the 9th grade until the war started. He then went to Afrin and stayed there until him and his family came to Greece on the 16th of March 2018. Ahmad was on the island of Samson for seven months before coming to Katsikas.“I like football and with participating in the marathon I want to try something new. Sport and running is important because it is useful for the health and for the body”. NabilNabil is from Syria, Afrin. He has been in Greece for 11 months. He stayed on Samos for 7 months, and has been in Katsikas for 4 months. Nabil used to exercise a lot in Syria, mainly fitness.“I like to run because it makes me fit and it makes my body looks good. I like to run the marathon because I want to challenge myself, and see if I am able to do it. I don’t have any work here, and if you do not work and you don’t do sport, you become lazy. I don’t want this. It is also nice to do sports together, that is what I like about this running group.”MortezaMorteza is from Afghanistan, Daikondi, but grew up in Iran. He is 21 years old. Before he left Iran, he graduated from High School. He left Iran in October 2017 and has been in Greece since then. Last year just before the half-marathon he injured his leg and could not join. This year he is attempting the full marathon."Running benefits my health and my aim is to win the race. In the past I was the champion in badminton in Turkey. Here, I want to continue sport. I want to run for my freedom of movement because everyone should have the right to move freely".QaisarQaisar is from Iraq. He is 34 years old. He has been in Greece for 1,5 years. He lived on Samos for 5 months and has been in Katsikas for 1 year. In Iraq Qaiser worked as a truckdriver and car mechanic, he loved his job.“When I was younger I ran every day after work. Now I run every day around Katsikas. It is good for my mental well being and better then sleeping the whole day. Because of the running I have to wake up in the morning, which is good. Joining in the marathon gives me a goal to work towards to, and it is beautiful to do something together.”HusseinHusseini is from Afghanistan, Samangana. He is 24 years old. He grew up in Iran and came to Greece October 2017. He was one of the runners who participated in the half-marathon of Olympia in April 2018, as well as the 30km Lake Run in Ioannina."I like exercising and running. It is good for my health. I am stuck in Greece and moved around from camp to camp. None of that is my choice. Participating in the run is my choice. I am choosing to run"MukhtarMukhtar is from Afghanistan, he is 24 years old. He has been in Greece for 1 year and 8 months. He first stayed in Lesvos for 7 months, and has been in Katsikas for 1 year and 1 month.“Running is important for the health and it is also fun. If you wake up and run in the morning, you will be fresh the whole day. I want to participate in the marathon because we do this as a group, which is something I like.”SamadSamad is from Afghanistan, Maydan Wardak. He is 25 years old. In Afghanistan he was a commandor in the army. He left Afghanistan in October 2017 and has been in Greece since then. Samad participated in the half-marathon last year and has been part of the running group since then."I like to run and be healthy. It is good for my body. I will run to open peoples eyes to the fact that the 'crisis' is far from over. We are still stuck in Greece with very little hope to go anywhere else"Other Ways You Can HelpAlthough the situation of refugees in Greece is not covered by the media anymore, people are still arriving to Greece everyday, fleeing war and injustice, trying to find a safe place to live their lives. Others have been stuck in Greece for years. It is important to remind everyone that the situation of refugees in Greece has not improved.For more information concerning our working space and the creative things that happen here take a look:https://www.facebook.com/HabibiWorks/https://habibi.works/ Stay tuned for updates on the runners and the training...
